## createElement()

`createElement()` creates a new HTML element in memory.

Example:

```javascript
let li = document.createElement("li");
```

Creates:

```html
<li></li>
```

The element is not visible until it is added to the webpage.

---

## appendChild()

`appendChild()` adds an element as a child of another element.

Example:

```javascript
let li = document.createElement("li");
li.innerText = "JavaScript";

document.querySelector("#skillList").appendChild(li);
```

Output:

```html
<ul id="skillList">
    <li>JavaScript</li>
</ul>
```

---

## Dynamic List Example

HTML:

```html
<input type="text" id="skillInput" placeholder="Enter Skill">
<button id="btn">Add Skill</button>

<ul id="skillList"></ul>
```

JavaScript:

```javascript
let button = document.querySelector("#btn");

button.addEventListener("click", function() {

    let skill = document.querySelector("#skillInput").value;

    let li = document.createElement("li");

    li.innerText = skill;

    document.querySelector("#skillList").appendChild(li);

});
```

---

## Why Create the Element Inside the Click Event?

A new `<li>` is created every time the button is clicked.

This allows multiple items to be added to the list.

---

## Key Takeaways

- `createElement()` creates new HTML elements.
- `appendChild()` adds elements to the webpage.
- New elements should be created when needed, such as after a button click.
- Dynamic DOM manipulation is used in real-world applications like To-Do Lists and chat apps.

